### TypeScript with React: Complex Patterns

TypeScript's real value in React goes beyond basic prop types. Generics enable reusable components that maintain full type safety across arbitrary data shapes. Three patterns worth knowing in depth:

```typescript
// 1. Generic component — type-safe for any data shape
interface ListProps<T> {
  items: T[];
  getKey: (item: T) => string;
  renderItem: (item: T) => React.ReactNode;
  emptyState?: React.ReactNode;
}

function List<T>({ items, getKey, renderItem, emptyState = <p>No items</p> }: ListProps<T>) {
  if (items.length === 0) return <>{emptyState}</>;
  return <ul>{items.map(item => <li key={getKey(item)}>{renderItem(item)}</li>)}</ul>;
}

// Usage: TypeScript infers T = User
<List<User>
  items={users}
  getKey={u => u.id}
  renderItem={u => <span>{u.name}</span>}
/>

// 2. Extending native element props (button with loading state)
type ButtonProps = React.ComponentPropsWithRef<'button'> & {
  loading?: boolean;
};

const Button = React.forwardRef<HTMLButtonElement, ButtonProps>(
  ({ loading, children, disabled, ...rest }, ref) => (
    <button ref={ref} disabled={disabled || loading} {...rest}>
      {loading ? 'Loading…' : children}
    </button>
  )
);
Button.displayName = 'Button';

// 3. Discriminated union — mutually exclusive prop shapes
type Action =
  | { variant: 'link'; href: string; onClick?: never }
  | { variant: 'button'; onClick: () => void; href?: never };

function ActionItem({ variant, label, ...props }: Action & { label: string }) {
  if (variant === 'link') return <a href={props.href}>{label}</a>;
  return <button onClick={props.onClick}>{label}</button>;
}

// TypeScript catches misuse at compile time:
// <ActionItem variant="link" onClick={() => {}} label="x" />  ← Error: onClick not allowed on link
```

**Common interview trap:** Using `any` as an escape hatch (`const ref = useRef<any>(null)`) defeats TypeScript's purpose. Use `unknown` with narrowing, or the correct DOM type (`HTMLInputElement`, `HTMLDivElement`). Another trap: not typing the generic in hooks — `useState()` without a type defaults to `undefined` union, losing null-safety. Prefer `useState<User | null>(null)` explicitly.

answer.ru:
### TypeScript с React: сложные паттерны

Реальная ценность TypeScript в React выходит за рамки базовых типов пропсов. Дженерики позволяют создавать переиспользуемые компоненты с полной типобезопасностью для любых форм данных. Три паттерна, заслуживающих глубокого понимания:

```typescript
// 1. Дженерик-компонент — типобезопасен для любой формы данных
interface ListProps<T> {
  items: T[];
  getKey: (item: T) => string;
  renderItem: (item: T) => React.ReactNode;
  emptyState?: React.ReactNode;
}

function List<T>({ items, getKey, renderItem, emptyState = <p>Нет элементов</p> }: ListProps<T>) {
  if (items.length === 0) return <>{emptyState}</>;
  return <ul>{items.map(item => <li key={getKey(item)}>{renderItem(item)}</li>)}</ul>;
}

// TypeScript выводит T = User
<List<User>
  items={users}
  getKey={u => u.id}
  renderItem={u => <span>{u.name}</span>}
/>

// 2. Расширение пропсов нативного элемента (кнопка с состоянием загрузки)
type ButtonProps = React.ComponentPropsWithRef<'button'> & {
  loading?: boolean;
};

const Button = React.forwardRef<HTMLButtonElement, ButtonProps>(
  ({ loading, children, disabled, ...rest }, ref) => (
    <button ref={ref} disabled={disabled || loading} {...rest}>
      {loading ? 'Загрузка…' : children}
    </button>
  )
);
Button.displayName = 'Button';

// 3. Размеченное объединение — взаимоисключающие формы пропсов
type Action =
  | { variant: 'link'; href: string; onClick?: never }
  | { variant: 'button'; onClick: () => void; href?: never };

function ActionItem({ variant, label, ...props }: Action & { label: string }) {
  if (variant === 'link') return <a href={props.href}>{label}</a>;
  return <button onClick={props.onClick}>{label}</button>;
}

// TypeScript ловит неверное использование на этапе компиляции:
// <ActionItem variant="link" onClick={() => {}} label="x" />  ← Ошибка
```

**Типичная ошибка на интервью:** Использовать `any` как выход (`const ref = useRef<any>(null)`) — это отменяет смысл TypeScript. Используйте `unknown` с сужением типов или правильный DOM-тип (`HTMLInputElement`, `HTMLDivElement`). Вторая ловушка: не указывать дженерик в хуках — `useState()` без типа по умолчанию будет `undefined`, теряя null-безопасность. Явно указывайте: `useState<User | null>(null)`.

answer.en:
### Lazy Loading and Code Splitting

Code splitting breaks the bundle into smaller chunks loaded on demand. `React.lazy` + `Suspense` provide native support: each `lazy()` call creates a separate chunk; bundlers (Webpack, Vite) detect `import()` calls and split automatically.

```typescript
import { lazy, Suspense } from 'react';
import { createBrowserRouter, RouterProvider, Outlet } from 'react-router-dom';
import { ErrorBoundary } from 'react-error-boundary';

// Each lazy() creates a separate bundle chunk — define at module level, not inside components
const Dashboard = lazy(() => import('./pages/Dashboard'));
const Settings = lazy(
  () => import(/* webpackChunkName: "settings" */ './pages/Settings')
);

function PageWrapper() {
  return (
    // Always pair Suspense with an ErrorBoundary — chunk load can fail
    <ErrorBoundary fallbackRender={({ error }) => <div>Failed to load: {error.message}</div>}>
      <Suspense fallback={<div className="page-loader">Loading…</div>}>
        <Outlet />
      </Suspense>
    </ErrorBoundary>
  );
}

const router = createBrowserRouter([
  {
    path: '/',
    element: <PageWrapper />,
    children: [
      { path: 'dashboard', element: <Dashboard /> },
      { path: 'settings', element: <Settings /> },
    ],
  },
]);

export default function App() {
  return <RouterProvider router={router} />;
}

// Prefetch a chunk on hover to eliminate perceived load time
function NavLink({ to, chunkImport, children }: { to: string; chunkImport: () => Promise<unknown>; children: React.ReactNode }) {
  return (
    <a href={to} onMouseEnter={() => chunkImport()}>
      {children}
    </a>
  );
}
// <NavLink to="/settings" chunkImport={() => import('./pages/Settings')}>Settings</NavLink>
```

**Common interview trap:** Defining `lazy()` inside a component body — `const Comp = lazy(() => import('./X'))` inside a render creates a new Promise every render, bypassing React's cache and re-loading the chunk. Always define lazy components at the module (top) level. Second trap: forgetting an `ErrorBoundary` around lazy components — chunk download failures (network errors, new deploys mid-session) crash the UI without one.

