### State Management Comparison

Context: built-in, good for simple global state (themes, auth), but causes unnecessary re-renders when unrelated state changes. Redux: centralized, predictable, DevTools, but boilerplate-heavy. Zustand: minimal, hook-based, no boilerplate, but smaller ecosystem.

Context for: theme, language, auth. Redux for: large apps with complex async flows, time-travel debugging needs. Zustand for: modern, small-to-medium apps wanting simplicity without Redux ceremony.

```typescript
// Zustand (recommended for modern apps)
import { create } from 'zustand';

const useStore = create((set) => ({
  user: null,
  setUser: (user) => set({ user }),
  logout: () => set({ user: null })
}));

// Use in components
function Profile() {
  const { user, logout } = useStore();
  return <button onClick={logout}>{user?.name}</button>;
}

// Context (simple use case)
const ThemeContext = createContext('light');
export function ThemeProvider({ children }) {
  const [theme, setTheme] = useState('light');
  return (
    <ThemeContext.Provider value={{ theme, setTheme }}>
      {children}
    </ThemeContext.Provider>
  );
}```


**Common interview trap:** Candidates over-engineer with Redux for simple apps or use Context when they need selector memoization—understand trade-offs.

